<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06108092 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06108092 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  RETAIL; SALE; STORE; COMPANY; EARNINGS; DECREASE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Ames Department Stores Inc. reported a fourth-quarter loss of $26.8 million, asignificant improvement over the $198.9 million loss suffered in the finalquarter of 1989.;    The loss amounted to 80 cents per share vs. a loss of$5.39 per share for the discount retailer, which filed for protection fromcreditors in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in April 1990.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  AMES DEPARTMENT STORES SLASHES 4TH-QUARTERLOSS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Net sales for the quarter ended Jan. 26 were $945.8 million, down 4.7percent from 1989's adjusted net sales of $992.9 million. The 1989 figureexcluded sales from 227 stores that were closed in a restructuring.;    Forthe year, Ames reported a net loss of $793.5 million, or $21.47 per share,compared with a net loss of $228.1 million, or $6.41 per share, for the prioryear.;    &quot;Despite substantial challenges and an unusually weak retail marketduring the 1990 Christmas season, we met or exceeded our principal financialgoals for the fourth quarter,&quot; said Stephen L. Pistner, Ames' chairman andchief executive officer.;    &quot;Since the Chapter 11 filing, we have madesignificant progress as we laid the foundation for further improvement in ouroperations,&quot; Pistner said.;    He said the company's current budget projectsan operating profit of $55 million for the fiscal year ending January 1992.;   Ames operates 455 stores in 17 Northeast states.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Rocky Hill, Conn.  </CITY><EDITION>  Street  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910417  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  213  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wedne